## Test Anti-Pattern Audit — `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| **Critical** | 6 |
| **Medium** | 2 |

This test class is a textbook **coverage-touching** suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is invoked (achieving 95% line coverage), but almost nothing is actually *verified*. Bugs in price calculation, search logic, CSV formatting, and removal all pass this suite undetected.

---

### Critical Findings

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The class methodically calls every method on `ProductCatalog` without meaningful assertions. 6 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**; 3 more assert only `IsNotNull` on a reference that can never be `null` (a `List<T>` or `string`). This is the root cause of your production bugs.

#### 2. No Assertion — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

```csharp
// BEFORE
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
// nothing asserted — did it persist? who knows

// FIX
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
```

#### 3. No Assertion — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)

The most dangerous one: `UpdatePrice` mutates stored state, yet the test never checks the new price. A bug in the `p with { Price = newPrice }` logic passes silently.

```csharp
// FIX
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

#### 4. No Assertion — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

Never verifies the product is actually gone. `Delete` could be a no-op and this test still passes.

```csharp
// FIX
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 5. No Assertion — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69)

A 10% discount is applied but the resulting prices are never checked. This is exactly the kind of math bug that reaches production.

```csharp
// FIX
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

#### 6. Trivial `IsNotNull` on Non-Nullable Returns — `SearchProducts_Works` (line 46), `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 55), `ExportToCsv_Works` (line 77)

`Search()` returns `List<Product>` and `ExportToCsv()` returns `string` — these can never be `null`. The assertions prove nothing.

```csharp
